HANDLING OUTLIERS

Data entry mistakes (typing 1000 instead of 100)

Measurement issues (faulty instruments)

Natural variations (rare real-world values)
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
df=pd.read_csv("steam_data_cleaned.csv")
df.head(10)
df.columns
Metacritic is a popular website that gives a score (0–100) to games, movies, and TV shows based on reviews from critics.
(df["Metacritic"]>100).sum()
(df["Metacritic"]<1).sum()
In this project, outliers were handled without using the IQR method.
Instead, invalid values were identified using domain knowledge.
The Metacritic score of 0 does not represent an actual rating, so it was treated as an unknown value and replaced with NaN.
We use it to represent missing or unknown values in numeric data.

| Option               | Problem                                                 |
| -------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| `0`                  | Looks like a real score (wrong)                         |
| `"Unknown"` (string) | Breaks numeric calculations & plotting                  |
| `np.nan`             | Treated as missing and still keeps the column numeric ✔ |

(df["PriceFinal"]<1).sum()
(df["PriceFinal"]>1000).sum()
df.head(30)
df.describe()
import numpy as np

df['Metacritic'] = df['Metacritic'].replace(0, np.nan)

(df["PriceFinal"]<1).sum()
(df["PriceFinal"]<1).sum()
df.to_csv('steam_data_cleaned.csv', index=False)
df.head()
df.to_csv('steam_data_cleaned.csv', index=False)
df.info()
df.describe()
df[df['RecommendationCount'] > 100000]
Q1 = df['RecommendationCount'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df['RecommendationCount'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

df['RecommendationCount'] = df['RecommendationCount'].clip(lower, upper)

(df['RecommendationCount'] > 100000).sum()

df.describe()
df.to_csv("steam_data_cleaned.csv", index=False)
